hands_on_practices.solution:
We wish to compute $F(\omega)=\mathcal{F}\{f(t)\}$ for 
$$f(t)=e^{-a(t-t_{0})^{2}}\,. $$

1.  Introduce the standard Gaussian $g(t)=e^{-a t^{2}}$ whose transform is 
   $$G(\omega)=\mathcal{F}\{g(t)\}
   =\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{a}}\;e^{-\frac{\omega^{2}}{4a}}\,. $$

2.  By the time-shifting property, since $f(t)=g(t-t_{0})$, 
   $$\mathcal{F}\{f(t)\}
   =e^{-\,i\omega t_{0}}\,G(\omega)
   =e^{-\,i\omega t_{0}}\,
     \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{a}}\;e^{-\frac{\omega^{2}}{4a}}
   =\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{a}}\;e^{-\frac{\omega^{2}}{4a}}\;e^{-\,i\omega t_{0}}\,. $$

3.  Using the differentiation-in-time property,
   $$\mathcal{F}\Bigl\{\frac{df(t)}{dt}\Bigr\}
   =i\omega\,\mathcal{F}\{f(t)\}
   =i\omega\,\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{a}}\;e^{-\frac{\omega^{2}}{4a}}\;e^{-\,i\omega t_{0}}\,. $$
